<font color="#FF0000">A SENSE OF BETRAYAL</font><br>
<tt>Thu Nov 28  1:59:41 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Dear Brett:<br><br>
I was in Vietnam in 1970-71, when you were six or seven years old.  I'm now almost 51, so I do have some perspective.  <br><br>
I think that the first thing I would ask is that you stop watching all the steriotyping of Vietnam vets.  There were a full range of people who served in Vietnam, a very few of whom fit the steriotype.  Most supplied the front lines, or worked in some other capacity.  <br><br>
To give you some other perspective, there are a bit over 50,000 names on Maya Lin's wall, our Vietnam Veteran's Memorial.  That's about the same number of people killed in the United States every year in traffic accidents.  I know, because after I served in Vietnam as a USAF Pararescueman, I also served on an ambulance service in Oregon.  You've heard that &quot;WAR IS HELL!&quot; above.  I'm here to tell you that carnage is hell anywhere, whether it's on highways or in Vietnam.  We had a poster in our alert room at DaNang which stated &quot;War is not healthy for children, and other living things.&quot;  Beside these words was a painting of a flower with its pedals falling off.<br><br>
Am I scarred by my experience in Vietnam?  No, and yes.  <br><br>
I'm very proud of the work we did there, which was combat air rescue.  I'm also proud of the people I served with, names such as Duane Hackney, Charlie King and others you haven't heard of but who should be American heros.  You've probably never heard of Steve Northern either.  My service in Vietnam did not scar me.<br><br>
So if there are scars, where are they from?  It has to do with the reception coming home, not the work we did there.  Picking up the body of a pilot in the Yellow Sea off Korea is not much different than picking up a body in Vietnam, or a body in Eugene, Oregon.  It is traumatic, but so is everyday life.<br><br>
I think that to understand the psychic of some Vietnam Vets, you will have to understand the sense of betrayal many feel at the political system which lied to the American people, and left the vets holding the goods.  This was our first real political war.  We could easily have won it; the Pentagon had plans for winning it (an invasion of North Vietnam would have done the trick) but we lost the will to do so.  Television played a role, because for the first time Americans could see the results, often immediately (and before we even knew about them).  It was therefore a sense that we had tried our hardest, sometimes repeatedly doing the same miserable things over and over again because some polititian thought it was best (when the military knew it would jeopardize their people).<br><br>
This has contributed to the sense that polititians are not looking out for what's best for the country, but only for what looks best for themselves.  I think this is the longest-lasting legacy of the Vietnam experience.  
